    "# Spacy \n",
    "Its a object oriented approach, \n",
    "it does not return list of strings -> it returns Doc object (like a container) that contains Token object with extra informations [Stop words etc]\n",
    "- spaCy is \"smarter.\" When you process text, it returns a Doc object, which is like a smart container. Inside this container are Token objects.\n",
    "- Think of a **Token** object as a \"folder\" for each word that contains a bunch of hidden \"sticky notes\" (attributes) describing that word.\n",
    "##### Breaking it down:\n",
    "- The Doc Object: This represents the entire original sentence. It \"owns\" the tokens and remembers their order.\n",
    "\n",
    "- The Token Object: Instead of just being the letters \"running\", it’s an object that knows its own \"identity.\"\n",
    "### The \"Extra Information\" (Attributes)\n",
    "Every token has built-in variables (attributes) you can check.   \n",
    "#### Here are the ones you mentioned:\n",
    "**token.is_stop:** A True/False value. It checks if the word is a \"Stop Word\" (common words like \"the\", \"is\", \"at\" that usually don't carry much meaning).  \n",
    "**token.pos_:** The Part of Speech. It tells you if the word is a NOUN, VERB, or ADJ.  \n",
    "**token.lemma_:** The \"base form\" of the word. (e.g., \"running\" becomes \"run\"). \n",
    "**token.is_punct:** A True/False value. Tells you if the token is just a comma or period.  \n"
   ]
